<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="123" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="6.[189,310,1121,1147]" box="[189,310,1121,1147]" pageId="6" pageNumber="123">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,310,1121,1147]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="6" pageNumber="123" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,310,1121,1147]" pageId="6" pageNumber="123">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[188,1401,1168,1862]" pageId="6" pageNumber="123">
<taxonomicName authority="Vargas, 2021" authorityName="Vargas" authorityYear="2021" box="[189,345,1168,1194]" class="Insecta" family="Heliodinidae" genus="Helioandesia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[189,345,1168,1194]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="123">Helioandesia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[354,463,1168,1194]" pageId="6" pageNumber="123" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
can be recognized by the following combination of morphological characters: (1) presence of CuP on forewing of female and male; (2) two bristles of unequal length in the female frenulum; (3) forewing mostly gray, ornamented with strongly bulging metallic spots, (4) two triangular processes on anterior margin of tergum VIII in the male abdomen; (5) sclerotization of the widened proximal part of the ductus bursae not reaching the ostium; (6) signum with proximal portion coarser than distal portion; (7) presence of an appendix bursae; (8) slightly swollen distal end of the saccus; and (9) a well-developed cornutus on the vesica. The mostly gray forewing pattern of 
<taxonomicName authority="Vargas, 2021" authorityName="Vargas" authorityYear="2021" box="[1242,1398,1379,1405]" class="Insecta" family="Heliodinidae" genus="Helioandesia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1242,1398,1379,1405]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="123">Helioandesia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[189,303,1415,1441]" pageId="6" pageNumber="123" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, ornamented with strongly bulging metallic spots, resembles that of the mainly Nearctic 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chambers" authorityYear="1876" box="[189,358,1449,1475]" class="Insecta" family="Heliodinidae" genus="Lithariapteryx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[189,358,1449,1475]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="123">Lithariapteryx</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, the latter lacks CuP in the forewing of female and male, has a single bristle in the female frenulum, and lacks a well-developed cornutus on the vesica. The female genitalia of 
<taxonomicName authority="Vargas, 2021" authorityName="Vargas" authorityYear="2021" box="[189,320,1520,1545]" class="Insecta" family="Heliodinidae" genus="Helioandesia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tarregai" status="gen. et sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[189,320,1520,1545]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="123">H. tarregai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[327,503,1520,1546]" pageId="6" pageNumber="123" rank="species">gen. et sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
are very similar to those of the Bolivian 
<taxonomicName authority="(Meyrick, 1932)" baseAuthorityName="Meyrick" baseAuthorityYear="1932" class="Insecta" family="Heliodinidae" genus="Lithariapteryx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="loriculata">
<emphasis box="[982,1275,1520,1546]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="123">Lithariapteryx loriculata</emphasis>
(Meyrick, 1932)
</taxonomicName>
in the shape of the transverse bridge, signum and antrum. However, 
<taxonomicName authority="Vargas, 2021" authorityName="Vargas" authorityYear="2021" box="[1080,1212,1556,1581]" class="Insecta" family="Heliodinidae" genus="Helioandesia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tarregai" status="gen. et sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1080,1212,1556,1581]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="123">H. tarregai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1219,1399,1555,1581]" pageId="6" pageNumber="123" rank="species">gen. et sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
lacks a V-shaped mark from costa on the forewing, has a sclerotization on the distal part of the ductus bursae and has the signum on the left margin of the corpus bursae, while 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Meyrick" baseAuthorityYear="1932" box="[1065,1213,1625,1651]" class="Insecta" family="Heliodinidae" genus="Lithariapteryx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="loriculata">
<emphasis box="[1065,1213,1625,1651]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="123">L. loriculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a V-shaped mark from the costa on the forewing, lacks sclerotization on the distal part of the ductus bursae and has the signum on the middle of the ventral part of the corpus bursae. The male of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Meyrick" baseAuthorityYear="1932" box="[1149,1299,1696,1722]" class="Insecta" family="Heliodinidae" genus="Lithariapteryx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="loriculata">
<emphasis box="[1149,1299,1696,1722]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="123">L. loriculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
remains unknown, impeding comparison with 
<taxonomicName authority="Vargas, 2021" authorityName="Vargas" authorityYear="2021" box="[639,770,1732,1757]" class="Insecta" family="Heliodinidae" genus="Helioandesia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tarregai" status="gen. et sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[639,770,1732,1757]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="123">H. tarregai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[779,957,1731,1757]" pageId="6" pageNumber="123" rank="species">gen. et sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
Two bristles of unequal length in the female frenulum of 
<taxonomicName authority="Vargas, 2021" authorityName="Vargas" authorityYear="2021" box="[432,588,1766,1792]" class="Insecta" family="Heliodinidae" genus="Helioandesia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[432,588,1766,1792]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="123">Helioandesia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[599,709,1767,1793]" pageId="6" pageNumber="123" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
resemble those of 
<taxonomicName authority="Meyrick, 1907" authorityName="Meyrick" authorityYear="1907" box="[942,1249,1766,1792]" class="Insecta" family="Heliodinidae" genus="Epicroesa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[942,1060,1767,1792]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="123">Epicroesa</emphasis>
Meyrick, 1907
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stainton" authorityYear="1854" box="[1264,1391,1766,1792]" class="Insecta" family="Heliodinidae" genus="Heliodines" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1264,1391,1766,1792]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="123">Heliodines</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Busck, 1900" authorityName="Busck" authorityYear="1900" box="[189,512,1801,1827]" class="Insecta" family="Heliodinidae" genus="Lamprolophus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[189,359,1801,1827]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="123">Lamprolophus</emphasis>
Busck, 1900
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Meyrick, 1927" authorityName="Meyrick" authorityYear="1927" box="[568,901,1801,1827]" class="Insecta" family="Heliodinidae" genus="Philocoristis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[568,718,1801,1827]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="123">Philocoristis</emphasis>
Meyrick, 1927
</taxonomicName>
. However, all these genera lack CuP in the forewing.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="124" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="7.[189,324,265,291]" box="[189,324,265,291]" pageId="7" pageNumber="124">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,324,265,291]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="7" pageNumber="124" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,324,265,291]" pageId="7" pageNumber="124">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[189,1398,311,408]" pageId="7" pageNumber="124">
The genus name is derived from the Greek ʻ 
<emphasis box="[729,799,311,337]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="124">helios</emphasis>
ʼ (sun), the root of the family name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Heinemann" authorityYear="1877" box="[1240,1395,311,337]" class="Insecta" family="Heliodinidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="124" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Heliodinidae</taxonomicName>
, and Andes, in reference to the Andes Range, among whose amazing landscapes the 
<typeStatus box="[1217,1268,347,373]" pageId="7" pageNumber="124">type</typeStatus>
species of 
<taxonomicName authority="Vargas, 2021" authorityName="Vargas" authorityYear="2021" box="[189,345,381,407]" class="Insecta" family="Heliodinidae" genus="Helioandesia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="124" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[189,345,381,407]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="124">Helioandesia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[353,460,382,408]" pageId="7" pageNumber="124" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
was discovered. The name is considered feminine in gender.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="128" pageId="7" pageNumber="124" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="7.[189,334,447,473]" box="[189,334,447,473]" pageId="7" pageNumber="124">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,334,447,473]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="7" pageNumber="124" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,334,447,473]" pageId="7" pageNumber="124">Description</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[188,1398,494,660]" box="[234,298,494,520]" pageId="7" pageNumber="124">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[234,298,494,520]" pageId="7" pageNumber="124">Male</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[188,1398,494,660]" pageId="7" pageNumber="124">
HEAD. Frons and vertex with appressed scales; narrow, elongated scales behind compound eyes. Antenna filiform, about 0.7 times as long as forewing, basal five segments of flagellum slightly broadened (
<figureCitation box="[198,292,599,625]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="7.[189,232,1928,1954]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,757,1889]" captionTargetId="figure-163@7.[189,1398,757,1889]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Fig. 3. Helioandesia tarregai gen. et sp. nov., ♂, holotype (IDEA-LEPI-2020-015). A. Dorsal view. B. Head, lateral. C. Basal flagellomeres of right antenna. D. Three bulging metallic spots on the basal half of forewing. E. Hair pencil from base of subcosta, ventral. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4452227" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4452227/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="124">Fig. 3C</figureCitation>
) due to narrow superimposed scales on dorsal side. Labial palpus (
<figureCitation box="[1129,1223,599,625]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="7.[189,232,1928,1954]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,757,1889]" captionTargetId="figure-163@7.[189,1398,757,1889]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Fig. 3. Helioandesia tarregai gen. et sp. nov., ♂, holotype (IDEA-LEPI-2020-015). A. Dorsal view. B. Head, lateral. C. Basal flagellomeres of right antenna. D. Three bulging metallic spots on the basal half of forewing. E. Hair pencil from base of subcosta, ventral. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4452227" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4452227/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="124">Fig. 3B</figureCitation>
) porrect, with appressed scales.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4452227" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4452227" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4452227/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="124" startId="7.[189,232,1928,1954]" targetBox="[189,1398,757,1889]" targetPageId="7">
<paragraph blockId="7.[189,1399,1928,2025]" pageId="7" pageNumber="124">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,269,1928,1954]" pageId="7" pageNumber="124">Fig. 3.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Vargas, 2021" authorityName="Vargas" authorityYear="2021" box="[280,542,1928,1954]" class="Insecta" family="Heliodinidae" genus="Helioandesia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="124" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tarregai" status="gen. et sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[280,542,1928,1954]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="124">Helioandesia tarregai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[552,740,1928,1954]" pageId="7" pageNumber="124" rank="species">gen. et sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, ♂, holotype (IDEA-LEPI-2020-015). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1209,1230,1928,1954]" pageId="7" pageNumber="124">A</emphasis>
. Dorsal view. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,209,1963,1989]" pageId="7" pageNumber="124">B</emphasis>
. Head, lateral. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[392,412,1963,1989]" pageId="7" pageNumber="124">C</emphasis>
. Basal flagellomeres of right antenna. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[873,894,1963,1989]" pageId="7" pageNumber="124">D</emphasis>
. Three bulging metallic spots on the basal half of forewing. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[394,414,1998,2024]" pageId="7" pageNumber="124">E</emphasis>
. Hair pencil from base of subcosta, ventral. Scale bar: 1 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="8.[188,1399,265,467]" pageId="8" pageNumber="125">
THORAX. Covered with appressed scales. Tibial spurs 0-2-4; metatibia with inner spur of proximal pair about twice as long as outer one. Forewing lanceolate (
<figureCitation box="[864,938,300,326]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="8.[188,231,1963,1989]" captionTargetBox="[190,1397,1272,1927]" captionTargetId="figure-364@8.[190,1397,1272,1927]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Fig. 4. Helioandesia tarregai gen. et sp. nov., ♀, paratype (IDEA-LEPI-2020-024), wing venation showing frenulum with two bristles of unequal length. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4452229" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4452229/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="125">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
), with strongly bulging metallic spots (
<figureCitation box="[198,332,335,362]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="7.[189,232,1928,1954]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,757,1889]" captionTargetId="figure-163@7.[189,1398,757,1889]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Fig. 3. Helioandesia tarregai gen. et sp. nov., ♂, holotype (IDEA-LEPI-2020-015). A. Dorsal view. B. Head, lateral. C. Basal flagellomeres of right antenna. D. Three bulging metallic spots on the basal half of forewing. E. Hair pencil from base of subcosta, ventral. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4452227" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4452227/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="125">Fig. 3A, D</figureCitation>
); hair pencil (
<figureCitation box="[499,589,335,361]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="7.[189,232,1928,1954]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,757,1889]" captionTargetId="figure-163@7.[189,1398,757,1889]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Fig. 3. Helioandesia tarregai gen. et sp. nov., ♂, holotype (IDEA-LEPI-2020-015). A. Dorsal view. B. Head, lateral. C. Basal flagellomeres of right antenna. D. Three bulging metallic spots on the basal half of forewing. E. Hair pencil from base of subcosta, ventral. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4452227" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4452227/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="125">Fig. 3E</figureCitation>
) from base of subcosta ventrally; 12 veins; five R, all separate; M1 and M2 separate; CuA1 and CuA2 separate, proximal part of latter lost; CuP present as tubular vein near margin; 1A+2A present. Hindwing (
<figureCitation box="[618,691,406,432]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="8.[188,231,1963,1989]" captionTargetBox="[190,1397,1272,1927]" captionTargetId="figure-364@8.[190,1397,1272,1927]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Fig. 4. Helioandesia tarregai gen. et sp. nov., ♀, paratype (IDEA-LEPI-2020-024), wing venation showing frenulum with two bristles of unequal length. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4452229" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4452229/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="125">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
) lanceolate, six veins; Sc+R1 and Rs separate; M1 and M2 stalked; CuA1 and CuA2 stalked; frenulum a single bristle.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[189,1399,506,674]" pageId="8" pageNumber="125">
ABDOMEN. Tergum VIII (
<figureCitation box="[487,580,506,533]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="9.[189,232,1857,1883]" captionTargetBox="[327,1261,319,1818]" captionTargetId="figure-11@9.[326,1261,319,1818]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Fig. 5. Male genitalia and eighth segment of Helioandesia tarregai gen. et sp. nov., ♂, paratype (IDEA- LEPI-2020-021). A. Male genitalia, ventral view, phallus removed. B. Phallus, lateral view. C. Tergum and pleural lobes of eighth segment. D. Socius, closed arrow in A. E. Small spine-like cornuti on the vesica, open arrow in A. F. Medial part of the cornutus. G. Coremata between pleural lobes of segment VIII and genitalia. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4452231" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4452231/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="125">Fig. 5C</figureCitation>
) triangular; anterior margin slightly concave, antero-lateral vertices as small processes slightly extending anteriorly beneath tergum VII; lateral margin widely convex; posterior margin about ¼ of anterior margin, with wide rounded notch in middle. Pleural lobe (
<figureCitation box="[1300,1389,577,604]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="9.[189,232,1857,1883]" captionTargetBox="[327,1261,319,1818]" captionTargetId="figure-11@9.[326,1261,319,1818]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Fig. 5. Male genitalia and eighth segment of Helioandesia tarregai gen. et sp. nov., ♂, paratype (IDEA- LEPI-2020-021). A. Male genitalia, ventral view, phallus removed. B. Phallus, lateral view. C. Tergum and pleural lobes of eighth segment. D. Socius, closed arrow in A. E. Small spine-like cornuti on the vesica, open arrow in A. F. Medial part of the cornutus. G. Coremata between pleural lobes of segment VIII and genitalia. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4452231" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4452231/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="125">Fig. 5C</figureCitation>
) triangular, with slightly sclerotized stripe near posterior margin. Sternum VIII not differentiated. Coremata (
<figureCitation box="[319,411,647,674]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="9.[189,232,1857,1883]" captionTargetBox="[327,1261,319,1818]" captionTargetId="figure-11@9.[326,1261,319,1818]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Fig. 5. Male genitalia and eighth segment of Helioandesia tarregai gen. et sp. nov., ♂, paratype (IDEA- LEPI-2020-021). A. Male genitalia, ventral view, phallus removed. B. Phallus, lateral view. C. Tergum and pleural lobes of eighth segment. D. Socius, closed arrow in A. E. Small spine-like cornuti on the vesica, open arrow in A. F. Medial part of the cornutus. G. Coremata between pleural lobes of segment VIII and genitalia. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4452231" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4452231/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="125">Fig. 5G</figureCitation>
) between pleural lobes and genitalia.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[188,1401,712,986]" pageId="8" pageNumber="125">
GENITALIA (
<figureCitation box="[316,390,712,739]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="9.[189,232,1857,1883]" captionTargetBox="[327,1261,319,1818]" captionTargetId="figure-11@9.[326,1261,319,1818]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Fig. 5. Male genitalia and eighth segment of Helioandesia tarregai gen. et sp. nov., ♂, paratype (IDEA- LEPI-2020-021). A. Male genitalia, ventral view, phallus removed. B. Phallus, lateral view. C. Tergum and pleural lobes of eighth segment. D. Socius, closed arrow in A. E. Small spine-like cornuti on the vesica, open arrow in A. F. Medial part of the cornutus. G. Coremata between pleural lobes of segment VIII and genitalia. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4452231" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4452231/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="125">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). Tegumen posteriorly expanded, somewhat conical, narrowing posteriorly. Gnathos absent. Socius (
<figureCitation box="[383,478,748,775]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="9.[189,232,1857,1883]" captionTargetBox="[327,1261,319,1818]" captionTargetId="figure-11@9.[326,1261,319,1818]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Fig. 5. Male genitalia and eighth segment of Helioandesia tarregai gen. et sp. nov., ♂, paratype (IDEA- LEPI-2020-021). A. Male genitalia, ventral view, phallus removed. B. Phallus, lateral view. C. Tergum and pleural lobes of eighth segment. D. Socius, closed arrow in A. E. Small spine-like cornuti on the vesica, open arrow in A. F. Medial part of the cornutus. G. Coremata between pleural lobes of segment VIII and genitalia. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4452231" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4452231/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="125">Fig. 5D</figureCitation>
) narrow, conical, with hair-like setae, apex coincides with that of tegumen. Saccus narrow, rod-shaped, about twice as long as tegumen, slightly broadened near base, distal end slightly swollen. Valva simple, with a few hair-like setae, costal margin broadly concave, ventral margin broadly convex, apex rounded. Phallus cylindrical, elongated, slightly longer than tegumen + saccus, slightly curved ventrally; vesica with prominent, long spine-like cornutus (
<figureCitation box="[1078,1201,888,915]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="9.[189,232,1857,1883]" captionTargetBox="[327,1261,319,1818]" captionTargetId="figure-11@9.[326,1261,319,1818]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Fig. 5. Male genitalia and eighth segment of Helioandesia tarregai gen. et sp. nov., ♂, paratype (IDEA- LEPI-2020-021). A. Male genitalia, ventral view, phallus removed. B. Phallus, lateral view. C. Tergum and pleural lobes of eighth segment. D. Socius, closed arrow in A. E. Small spine-like cornuti on the vesica, open arrow in A. F. Medial part of the cornutus. G. Coremata between pleural lobes of segment VIII and genitalia. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4452231" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4452231/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="125">Fig. 5B, F</figureCitation>
) slightly smaller than half of phallus, and group of small spine-like cornuti (
<figureCitation box="[902,994,924,951]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="9.[189,232,1857,1883]" captionTargetBox="[327,1261,319,1818]" captionTargetId="figure-11@9.[326,1261,319,1818]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Fig. 5. Male genitalia and eighth segment of Helioandesia tarregai gen. et sp. nov., ♂, paratype (IDEA- LEPI-2020-021). A. Male genitalia, ventral view, phallus removed. B. Phallus, lateral view. C. Tergum and pleural lobes of eighth segment. D. Socius, closed arrow in A. E. Small spine-like cornuti on the vesica, open arrow in A. F. Medial part of the cornutus. G. Coremata between pleural lobes of segment VIII and genitalia. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4452231" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4452231/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="125">Fig. 5E</figureCitation>
); insertion of ductus ejaculatorius near basal third of phallus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[187,1399,1025,1121]" box="[234,325,1025,1051]" pageId="8" pageNumber="125">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[234,325,1025,1051]" pageId="8" pageNumber="125">Female</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[187,1399,1025,1121]" pageId="8" pageNumber="125">
Mainly similar to male, but hindwing with two asymmetrical bristles on frenulum (
<figureCitation box="[1137,1207,1060,1086]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="8.[188,231,1963,1989]" captionTargetBox="[190,1397,1272,1927]" captionTargetId="figure-364@8.[190,1397,1272,1927]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Fig. 4. Helioandesia tarregai gen. et sp. nov., ♀, paratype (IDEA-LEPI-2020-024), wing venation showing frenulum with two bristles of unequal length. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4452229" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4452229/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="125">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
), and abdominal segment VIII not modified as in male.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[189,1399,1160,1222]" lastBlockId="11.[189,1398,265,327]" lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="128" pageId="8" pageNumber="125">
GENITALIA (
<figureCitation box="[314,386,1160,1187]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="10.[191,234,1927,1953]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,559,1861]" captionTargetId="figure-92@10.[189,1398,559,1861]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Fig. 6. Female genitalia of Helioandesia tarregai gen. et sp. nov., ♀, paratype (IDEA-LEPI-2020-024) A. Female genitalia, ventral view. B. Papillae analis. C. Ornamentation of the proximal part of the signum. D. Ornamentation of the distal part of the signum. Scale bar: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4452233" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4452233/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="125">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
). Papillae anales (
<figureCitation box="[599,689,1160,1187]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="10.[191,234,1927,1953]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,559,1861]" captionTargetId="figure-92@10.[189,1398,559,1861]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Fig. 6. Female genitalia of Helioandesia tarregai gen. et sp. nov., ♀, paratype (IDEA-LEPI-2020-024) A. Female genitalia, ventral view. B. Papillae analis. C. Ornamentation of the proximal part of the signum. D. Ornamentation of the distal part of the signum. Scale bar: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4452233" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4452233/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="125">Fig. 6B</figureCitation>
) narrow, elongated, slightly sclerotized, with hair-like setae. Posterior apophysis rod-like, about twice as long as papillae anales. Anterior apophysis rod-like, slightly shorter than posterior apophysis. Transverse bridge as rectangular transversal band, anterior vertices fused with posterior end of anterior apophyses. Ostium bursae membranous. Ductus bursae narrow, mainly membranous; proximal fourth widened, with distal half sclerotized; slightly widened and sclerotized near corpus bursae. Ductus seminalis arises on distal fourth of ductus bursae. Corpus bursae mainly membranous, lenticular; signum on left side, narrow, elongated, minutely sculptured, proximal (
<figureCitation box="[199,291,441,468]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="10.[191,234,1927,1953]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,559,1861]" captionTargetId="figure-92@10.[189,1398,559,1861]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Fig. 6. Female genitalia of Helioandesia tarregai gen. et sp. nov., ♀, paratype (IDEA-LEPI-2020-024) A. Female genitalia, ventral view. B. Papillae analis. C. Ornamentation of the proximal part of the signum. D. Ornamentation of the distal part of the signum. Scale bar: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4452233" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4452233/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="127">Fig. 6C</figureCitation>
) portion coarser than distal (
<figureCitation box="[637,730,441,468]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="10.[191,234,1927,1953]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,559,1861]" captionTargetId="figure-92@10.[189,1398,559,1861]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Fig. 6. Female genitalia of Helioandesia tarregai gen. et sp. nov., ♀, paratype (IDEA-LEPI-2020-024) A. Female genitalia, ventral view. B. Papillae analis. C. Ornamentation of the proximal part of the signum. D. Ornamentation of the distal part of the signum. Scale bar: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4452233" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4452233/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="127">Fig. 6D</figureCitation>
) portion, slightly invaginate and broadened subapically, length about ¾ that of corpus bursae. Appendix bursae spherical, membranous, on the middle of corpus bursae, on the opposite side of signum.
</paragraph>
